sed","before 1334":"before 1334","Abt 1325":"about 1325","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1334":"1334","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1356":"about 1356","1328":"1328","Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Flore, Northamptonshire, England":"Flore, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tilly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a shortened form of <b>Tilling</b>, which itself is a patronymic from   Till  .","English and Irish: variant of   Tilley  .","Irish: variant of   Tully  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Till","meanings":["English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Till</i>, a pet form of Old French <i>Matild(e)</i> (in its Latin form <i>Matilda</i>), which was an alternative to <i>Maud</i>; see   Maude   2. A diminutive form occurs in   Tillotson  .","North German: variant of   Thiel  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Tilly was born about 1325, in Flore, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Henry Tilly, was 32 and his mother, Maud Fauldingworth, was 27. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Northamptonshire. He died in 1362, at the age of 38."},"et":{"Abt 1325–1362":"umbes 1325–1362","1325–1362":"1325–1362","1328–1355":"1328–1355","1356–Female":"1356–Surnud","1295–1334":"1295–1334","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","before 1334":"enne 1334","Abt 1325":"umbes 1325","1362":"1362","1295":"1295","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1334":"1334","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","about 1356":"umbes 1356","1328":"1328","Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Flore, Northamptonshi